1
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Good morning Mr. Thompson, I'm Dr. Ramirez. I need to take a full medical history from you today — is that alright?

2
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:06,500
Yes, that's absolutely fine, go ahead.

3
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:10,000
Can you tell me what brings you in today? What's the main problem?

4
00:00:10,500 --> 00:00:14,500
I've had crushing chest pain for about three hours, and it's radiating down my left arm into my jaw.

5
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:18,000
On a scale of zero to ten, how severe is the pain right now?

6
00:00:18,500 --> 00:00:20,500
It's an eight out of ten, maybe a nine when it's at its worst.

7
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:24,000
When did it start, and was there anything that triggered it?

8
00:00:24,500 --> 00:00:28,500
It started about three hours ago while I was climbing the stairs at work. It came on suddenly.

9
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:32,000
Are there any associated symptoms — shortness of breath, nausea, sweating?

10
00:00:32,500 --> 00:00:36,500
Yes, I've been short of breath, I feel nauseated, and I'm sweating quite a lot — diaphoretic.

11
00:00:37,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Do you have any allergies to medications or foods?

12
00:00:40,500 --> 00:00:43,500
I'm allergic to Penicillin — it gives me a severe rash and hives.

13
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,000
What medications are you currently taking?

14
00:00:47,500 --> 00:00:51,000
I take Metformin 500 milligrams twice daily for my type 2 diabetes.

15
00:00:51,500 --> 00:00:55,000
I'm also on Lisinopril 10 milligrams once a day for high blood pressure.

16
00:00:55,500 --> 00:00:58,500
And Atorvastatin 40 milligrams at bedtime for cholesterol.

17
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:02,000
Any past medical history I should know about?

18
00:01:02,500 --> 00:01:06,000
I was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes about three years ago.

19
00:01:06,500 --> 00:01:09,500
I've had essential hypertension for about five years now.

20
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
High cholesterol, diagnosed about two years ago.

21
00:01:13,500 --> 00:01:16,500
Any previous surgeries or hospital stays?

22
00:01:17,000 --> 00:01:20,500
I had an appendectomy back in 2010 — no complications, straightforward.

23
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:24,500
I also had a right knee arthroscopy in 2018.

24
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:28,000
What about your family medical history?

25
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:32,500
My father had a heart attack at 52 and also has type 2 diabetes.

26
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:36,500
My mother has hypertension, and she had breast cancer but she's in remission.

27
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:40,000
My brother has type 2 diabetes as well, diagnosed at 45.

28
00:01:40,500 --> 00:01:43,500
When was your last flu shot and Covid booster?

29
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:47,500
I got the flu vaccine about a month ago, right arm, lot number was 4AB23.

30
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Covid booster was three months ago, I think it was Pfizer.

31
00:01:51,500 --> 00:01:54,500
Tetanus booster five years ago.

32
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:57,500
Do you smoke or drink alcohol?

33
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:02,000
I quit smoking five years ago. I used to smoke a pack a day for about twenty years.

34
00:02:02,500 --> 00:02:05,500
I drink alcohol socially — a beer or two on weekends.

35
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:08,500
What do you do for work, and what's your living situation?

36
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:12,500
I work as a construction foreman. I live with my wife in a single-family home.

37
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:16,500
Let me review some point-of-care labs. Your last HbA1c was 7.2 percent about two weeks ago.

38
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:20,000
Fasting glucose was 140 milligrams per deciliter at that visit.

39
00:02:20,500 --> 00:02:23,500
You're doing daily self-monitoring of blood glucose — glad to hear that.

40
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:27,000
Your last HIV screening came back negative.

41
00:02:27,500 --> 00:02:30,500
Syphilis screening was non-reactive.

42
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:34,000
Okay, let me take your vital signs now. Blood pressure is 165 over 95.

43
00:02:34,500 --> 00:02:37,500
Heart rate is 108 beats per minute and regular.

44
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:40,500
Temperature is 98.6 degrees Fahrenheit.

45
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:44,000
Oxygen saturation is 96 percent on room air.

46
00:02:44,500 --> 00:02:47,500
You're six feet tall and weigh 210 pounds today.

47
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:50,500
That puts your BMI at approximately 28.5.

48
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:54,500
On physical exam — patient appears diaphoretic and in moderate distress.

49
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:59,000
HEENT: pupils equal, round, reactive to light. No jugular venous distension.

50
00:02:59,500 --> 00:03:02,500
Neck: supple, no lymphadenopathy, thyroid normal to palpation.

51
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,500
Cardiovascular: tachycardic, regular rhythm, S1 and S2 present, no murmurs, rubs, or gallops.

52
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:11,000
Lungs: clear to auscultation bilaterally, no wheezes or crackles.

53
00:03:11,500 --> 00:03:14,500
Abdomen: soft, non-tender, no masses or organomegaly, bowel sounds active.

54
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:18,000
Musculoskeletal: full range of motion in all extremities, no edema.

55
00:03:18,500 --> 00:03:22,000
Neurologic: alert and oriented times three, cranial nerves two through twelve intact.

56
00:03:22,500 --> 00:03:25,500
Skin: diaphoretic, no rashes, no lesions, good turgor.

57
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:29,000
Psychological: anxious but cooperative, appropriate affect, no suicidal ideation.

58
00:03:29,500 --> 00:03:34,500
My primary assessment is acute coronary syndrome, rule out STEMI — ICD-10 I20.0.

59
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,500
Secondary diagnosis: poorly controlled type 2 diabetes, ICD-10 E11.65.

60
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:42,000
Also essential hypertension, ICD-10 I10.

61
00:03:42,500 --> 00:03:47,000
Plan: Order a stat 12-lead EKG and troponin I, repeat in three hours.

62
00:03:47,500 --> 00:03:50,500
Order chest X-ray and complete blood count, basic metabolic panel.

63
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:54,500
Start aspirin 325 milligrams chewed now.

64
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:58,500
Sublingual nitroglycerin 0.4 milligrams as needed for chest pain.

65
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:02,500
Admit for cardiac monitoring and cardiology consultation.

66
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,500
Follow-up with cardiology in 48 hours after discharge.

67
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:10,500
Patient education: discussed warning signs of heart attack, low-sodium diet, and smoking cessation reinforced.

68
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:14,500
Care coordination: referral placed to cardiology and diabetes educator.
